g and vulnerabilities**\\n\\nI’m evaluating the implications of testing the YAML module instead of the core. This could introduce potential vulnerabilities like those from Snake YAML, which I'm thinking we don’t need. I want to ensure the return is valid JSON without any markdown, and I should keep the summary concise. \\n\\nIt might be okay to say \\\"None\\\" for agent guidance but consider using an empty string if there's no other guidance. I’m also unsure if I need to mention research facts in the summary. The `hoplite-core` does have built-in features, which is worth noting.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"no_action\",\n  \"summary\": \"hoplite-core resolves with only Kotlin/coroutines dependencies and includes built-in property sources, default decoders, and a Java .properties/.props parser, so meaningful core coverage can be generated without extra Maven dependencies, Docker services, or driver-level environment setup.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"Most README examples use YAML and require the optional hoplite-yaml module, but that is not required for hoplite-core coverage because Java properties and Map/System/Environment property sources are built in.\",\n    \"If generated tests copy YAML/JSON/TOML/HOCON examples verbatim, they will need the matching optional Hoplite parser module; prefer built-in .properties or in-memory property sources for this artifact unless verification shows otherwise.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0ef2b42806a91855016a41a256295c819081d988678dd0ab2b\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 895, "output": 701, "cacheRead": 38400, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 39996, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782686282826, "responseId": "resp_0ef2b42806a91855016a41a24b4f648190a3f4a2